(144, 1, '2012-10-29 11:32:23', '2012-10-29 11:32:23', 'Decentralization is meant to deepen democracy, improve public services, and make government more accountable. But evidence from across the globe is contradictory. Is it an empty fashion? A giant mistake? Jean-Paul Faguet uses the remarkable case of Bolivia to investigate reform over a generation. Decentralization succeeded in Bolivia because change was driven by smaller, poorer municipalities prioritizing their greatest needs. Faguet combines broad econometric data with deep qualitative evidence to plumb the social underpinnings of governance. To understand decentralization, he argues, we must understand governance from the ground up.\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><iframe src="//www.youtube.com/embed/5Ap-D23rAvg?rel=0" height="315" width="560" allowfullscreen="" frameborder="0"></iframe></p>', 'Dr Jean-Paul Faguet discusses his new book at Berkeley', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'dr-jean-paul-faguet-discusses-his-new-book-at-berkeley', '', '', '2013-12-03 11:34:35', '2013-12-03 11:34:35', '', 0, 'http://governancefrombelow.net/?p=144', 0, 'post', '', 0),
